{{Chembox | ImageFile = Hydroxymatairesinol.svg | ImageSize = 150px | ImageAlt = | IUPACName = (3R,4R)-4-[(S)-Hydroxy(4-hydroxy-3-methoxyphenyl)methyl]-3-(4-hydroxy-3-methoxybenzyl)dihydro-2(3H)-furanone | SystematicName = (3R,4R)-4-[(S)-Hydroxy(4-hydroxy-3-methoxyphenyl)methyl]-3-(4-hydroxy-3-methoxybenzyl)dihydro-2(3H)-furanone |Section1={{Chembox Identifiers | Abbreviations = | CASNo = | EINECS = | PubChem = 10948757 | ChemSpiderID = 9123982 | SMILES = COC1=C(C=CC(=C1)C[C@@H]2[C@H](COC2=O)[C@@H](C3=CC(=C(C=C3)O)OC)O)O | InChI = 1/C20H22O7/c1-25-17-8-11(3-5-15(17)21)7-13-14(10-27-20(13)24)19(23)12-4-6-16(22)18(9-12)26-2/h3-6,8-9,13-14,19,21-23H,7,10H2,1-2H3/t13-,14+,19-/m1/s1 | InChIKey = UKHWOLNMBQSCLJ-BIENJYKABV | StdInChI = 1S/C20H22O7/c1-25-17-8-11(3-5-15(17)21)7-13-14(10-27-20(13)24)19(23)12-4-6-16(22)18(9-12)26-2/h3-6,8-9,13-14,19,21-23H,7,10H2,1-2H3/t13-,14+,19-/m1/s1 | StdInChIKey = UKHWOLNMBQSCLJ-BIENJYKASA-N}} |Section2={{Chembox Properties | Formula = C<sub>20</sub>H<sub>22</sub>O<sub>7</sub> | MolarMass = 374.384 | Appearance = | Density = | MeltingPt = | BoilingPt = | Solubility = }} |Section3={{Chembox Hazards | MainHazards = | FlashPt = | AutoignitionPt = }} }}
'''Hydroxymatairesinol''' (HMR) is a [[lignan]] found in [[Picea abies|Norway spruce]] (''Picea abies'').<ref name="Saarinen">{{cite journal |last=Saarinen |first=NM |last2=Warri |first2=A |last3=Makela |first3=SI |last4=Eckerman |first4=C |last5=Reunanen |first5=M |last6=Ahotupa |first6=M |last7=Salmi |first7=SM |last8=Franke |first8=AA |last9=Kangas |first9=L |last10=Santti |first10=R |display-authors=3 |date=2000 |title=Hydroxymatairesinol, a novel enterolactone precursor with antitumor properties from coniferous tree (Picea abies). |journal=Nutrition and Cancer |volume=36 |issue=2 |pages=207–16 |doi=10.1207/S15327914NC3602_10 |pmid=10890032}}</ref> It is an [[enterolactone]] precursor with anticancer activities. In rats, HMR decreased the volume of induced tumours and stabilised established tumours, as well as preventing the development of new tumours.<ref name=Saarinen/> It has also shown anti-oxidant properties ''in vitro''.<ref name=Saarinen/>
HMR's chemical structure is similar to [[matairesinol]].<ref name="Cosentino">{{cite journal |last=Cosentino |first=M |last2=Marino |first2=F |last3=Ferrari |first3=M |last4=Rasini |first4=E |last5=Bombelli |first5=R |last6=Luini |first6=A |last7=Legnaro |first7=M |last8=Delle Canne |first8=MG |last9=Luzzani |first9=M |last10=Crema |first10=F |last11=Paracchini |first11=S |last12=Lecchini |first12=S |display-authors=3 |date=August 2007 |url=http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S1043661807000990 |title=Estrogenic activity of 7-hydroxymatairesinol potassium acetate (HMR/lignan) from Norway spruce (Picea abies) knots and of its active metabolite enterolactone in MCF-7 cells. |journal=Pharmacological Research |volume=56 |issue=2 |pages=140–7 |doi=10.1016/j.phrs.2007.05.001 |pmid=17572100}}</ref> At high concentrations, HMR has estrogenic properties, which are considerably weaker than those of [[estradiol]].<ref name=Cosentino/>
